WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:04.059
- I watched my agent happily click the "I'm
not a robot" button. I made the agent

00:00:04.220 --> 00:00:07.720
very aware. Like, it knows
what his source code is. It

00:00:07.760 --> 00:00:11.340
understands th- how it
sits and runs in its own

00:00:11.400 --> 00:00:15.240
harness. It knows where
documentation is. It knows which

00:00:15.380 --> 00:00:19.380
model it runs. It understands its own
system that made it very easy for an agent

00:00:19.390 --> 00:00:22.600
to... Oh, you don't like
anything? You just prompted it to

00:00:22.640 --> 00:00:26.520
existence, and then the agent would
just modify its own software. People

00:00:26.540 --> 00:00:30.460
talk about self-modifying software, I just
built it. I actually think wipe coding is

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:31.280
a slur.

00:00:31.340 --> 00:00:33.080
- You prefer agentic engineering?

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:37.000
- Yeah, I always tell people I'd- I do
agentic engineering, and then maybe after

00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:40.560
3:00 AM, I switch to wipe coding, and
then I have regrets on the next day.

00:00:40.600 --> 00:00:42.060
- What a walk of shame.

00:00:42.080 --> 00:00:45.360
- Yeah, you just have to clean up
and, like, fix your sh- shit.

00:00:45.440 --> 00:00:46.520
- We've all been there.

00:00:46.580 --> 00:00:50.520
- I used to write really long prompts. And

00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:54.550
by writing, I mean, I don't write, I- I-
I talk, you know? These- these hands are,

00:00:54.580 --> 00:00:58.480
like, too- too precious for
writing now. I just- I just use

00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:00.660
bespoke prompts to build my software.

00:01:00.700 --> 00:01:04.500
- So, you, for real, with all those
terminals, are using voice?

00:01:04.560 --> 00:01:07.350
- Yeah. I used to do it very extensively,

00:01:08.600 --> 00:01:11.480
to the point where there was a
period where I lost my voice.

00:01:13.060 --> 00:01:16.760
- I mean, I have to ask you, just
curious. I- I know you've probably

00:01:16.820 --> 00:01:20.640
gotten huge offers from major companies.

00:01:21.600 --> 00:01:27.440
Can you speak to who you're
considering working with?

00:01:27.500 --> 00:01:28.940
- Yeah.

00:01:30.620 --> 00:01:34.560
- The following is a conversation
with Peter Steinberger, creator

00:01:34.620 --> 00:01:38.110
of OpenClaw, formerly known as MoldBot,

00:01:38.240 --> 00:01:41.940
ClawedBot, Clawdus, Claude,
spelled with a W as in

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:45.520
lobster claw. Not to be confused
with Claud, the AI model from

00:01:45.540 --> 00:01:49.140
Anthropic, spelled with a U. In fact, this

00:01:49.180 --> 00:01:52.940
confusion is the reason
Anthropic kindly asked Peter to

00:01:52.980 --> 00:01:56.860
change the name to OpenClaw. So, what is

00:01:56.900 --> 00:02:00.670
OpenClaw? It's an open-source AI
agent that has taken over the

00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:05.420
tech world in a matter of days,
exploding in popularity, reaching over

00:02:06.360 --> 00:02:10.139
180,000 stars on GitHub,
and spawning the social

00:02:10.180 --> 00:02:14.170
network mold book, where AI
agents post manifestos and

00:02:14.220 --> 00:02:18.170
debate consciousness, creating a
mix of excitement and fear in the

00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:22.130
general public. And a
kind of AI psychosis, a

00:02:22.180 --> 00:02:25.540
mix of clickbait fearmongering
and genuine, fully

00:02:25.580 --> 00:02:29.070
justifiable concern about the
role of AI in our digital,

00:02:29.100 --> 00:02:32.640
interconnected human world.
OpenClaw, as its tagline

00:02:32.740 --> 00:02:36.580
states, is the AI that
actually does things. It's an

00:02:36.620 --> 00:02:40.600
autonomous AI assistant that lives
in your computer, has access to

00:02:40.620 --> 00:02:44.220
all of your stuff, if you let it,
talks to you through Telegram,

00:02:44.260 --> 00:02:47.920
WhatsApp, Signal, iMessage, and
whatever else messaging client.

00:02:48.020 --> 00:02:55.120
Uses whatever AI model you like, including
Claude Opus 4.6 and GPT 5.3 Codex,

00:02:56.400 --> 00:03:00.320
all to do stuff for you.
Many people are calling

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:04.300
this one of the biggest moments in the
recent history of AI, since the launch of

00:03:04.340 --> 00:03:08.300
ChatGPT in November 2022.
The ingredients for this

00:03:08.340 --> 00:03:12.200
kind of AI agent were all there,
but putting it all together in a

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:16.160
system that definitively takes
a step forward over the line

00:03:16.200 --> 00:03:19.920
from language to agency, from
ideas to actions, in a way that

00:03:19.980 --> 00:03:23.970
created a useful assistant that
feels like one who gets you and

00:03:24.060 --> 00:03:28.020
learns from you, in an open
source, community-driven way, is

00:03:28.040 --> 00:03:32.000
the reason OpenClaw took
the internet by storm.

00:03:32.060 --> 00:03:36.000
Its power, in large part, comes from the fact
that you can give it access to all of your

00:03:36.080 --> 00:03:40.070
stuff and give it permission to
do anything with that stuff in

00:03:40.120 --> 00:03:47.060
order to be useful to you. This is very
powerful, but it is also dangerous. OpenClaw

00:03:47.100 --> 00:03:50.060
represents freedom, but with freedom comes

00:03:50.100 --> 00:03:54.040
responsibility. With it, you
can own and have control

00:03:54.080 --> 00:03:57.740
over your data, but precisely
because you have this control, you

00:03:57.820 --> 00:04:01.760
also have the responsibility to
protect it from cybersecurity

00:04:01.820 --> 00:04:05.060
threats of various kinds. There
are great ways to protect

00:04:05.080 --> 00:04:08.280
yourself, but the threats and
vulnerabilities are out there.

00:04:09.020 --> 00:04:12.700
Again, a powerful AI agent
with system- level access is a

00:04:12.740 --> 00:04:16.680
security minefield, but it also
represents the future. Because

00:04:16.740 --> 00:04:20.370
when done well and securely,
it can be extremely useful

00:04:20.420 --> 00:04:26.770
to each of us humans as a personal assistant.
We discuss all of this with Peter, and

00:04:26.860 --> 00:04:30.060
also discuss his
big-picture programming and

00:04:30.120 --> 00:04:32.740
entrepreneurship life story,
which I think is truly

00:04:32.780 --> 00:04:36.560
inspiring. He spent 13
years building PSPDF

00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:39.780
Kit, which is a software used on a billion

00:04:39.790 --> 00:04:43.770
devices. He sold it, and for a brief time,

00:04:43.820 --> 00:04:47.670
fell out of love with programming,
vanished for three years, and

00:04:47.700 --> 00:04:51.680
then came back, rediscovered his
love for programming, and built,

00:04:51.720 --> 00:04:55.560
in a very short time, an open
source AI agent that took the

00:04:55.600 --> 00:04:59.540
internet by storm. He is,
in many ways, the symbol

00:04:59.580 --> 00:05:03.500
of the AI revolution happening in
the programming world. There was the

00:05:03.540 --> 00:05:10.850
ChatGPT moment in 2022, the DeepSeek moment
in 2025, and now, in '26, we're living

00:05:10.940 --> 00:05:15.160
through the OpenClaw moment,
the age of the lobster.

00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:19.920
The start of the agentic AI
revolution. What a time to be

00:05:19.960 --> 00:05:23.800
alive. This is a Lex Fridman
podcast. To support it, please

00:05:23.820 --> 00:05:27.640
check out our sponsors in the description,
or you can also find links to contact

00:05:27.680 --> 00:05:31.660
me, ask questions, give
feedback, and so on.

00:05:31.680 --> 00:05:35.400
And now, dear friends,
here's Peter Steinberger.

00:05:36.520 --> 00:05:40.180
The one and only, the
Clawed Father. Actually,

00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:43.750
Benjamin predicted it in his tweet.
"The following is a conversation with

00:05:43.820 --> 00:05:47.240
Claude, a respected crustacean." It's a

00:05:47.280 --> 00:05:51.080
hilarious-looking picture of a
lobster in a suit, so I think the

00:05:51.120 --> 00:05:54.620
prophecy has been fulfilled. Let's

00:05:54.660 --> 00:05:58.540
go to this moment when you
built a prototype in one

00:05:58.660 --> 00:06:02.500
hour, that was the early version
of OpenClaw. I think this,

00:06:02.600 --> 00:06:06.220
Story's really inspiring to
a lot of people because this

00:06:06.360 --> 00:06:09.918
prototype led to something that
just took the internet by storm....

00:06:10.008 --> 00:06:13.657
and became the fastest-growing
repository in GitHub history,

00:06:13.708 --> 00:06:19.788
with now over 175,000 stars. So, what
was the story of the one-hour prototype?

00:06:20.148 --> 00:06:23.288
- You know, I wanted that since April.

00:06:23.408 --> 00:06:25.878
- A personal assistant.
AI personal assistant.

00:06:25.888 --> 00:06:30.308
- Yeah. And I, I played around with
some other things, like even

00:06:31.528 --> 00:06:35.468
stuff that gets all my WhatsApp,
and I could just run queries

00:06:35.508 --> 00:06:41.028
on it. That was back when we had
GPT-4.1, with the one million context

00:06:41.068 --> 00:06:47.108
window. And I, I pulled in all the
data and then just asked him questions

00:06:47.208 --> 00:06:50.018
like, "What makes this
friendship meaningful?"

00:06:50.028 --> 00:06:50.428
- Mm-hmm.

00:06:50.448 --> 00:06:54.068
- And I got some, some really profound

00:06:55.248 --> 00:06:58.948
results. Like, I sent it to my friends
and they got, like, teary eyes.

00:06:59.708 --> 00:07:01.368
- So, there's something there.

00:07:01.388 --> 00:07:05.218
- Yeah. But then I... I thought
all the labs will, will,

00:07:05.488 --> 00:07:09.378
will work on that. So
I, I moved on to other

00:07:09.468 --> 00:07:12.828
things, and that was still
very much in my early days of

00:07:12.888 --> 00:07:16.668
experimenting and pl- playing.
You know, you have to...

00:07:16.768 --> 00:07:21.188
That's how you learn. You just like,
you do stuff and you play. And

00:07:22.248 --> 00:07:26.108
time flew by and it was November.
I wanted to make sure that

00:07:26.168 --> 00:07:30.088
the thing I started is actually happening.
I was annoyed that it didn't exist, so

00:07:30.108 --> 00:07:35.788
I just prompted it into existence.

00:07:36.168 --> 00:07:38.988
- I mean, that's the beginning of the
hero's journey of the entrepreneur,

00:07:39.028 --> 00:07:42.968
right? And you've even
with your original story

00:07:42.988 --> 00:07:46.688
with PS PDF kit, it's like, "Why
does this not exist? Let me build

00:07:46.748 --> 00:07:52.048
it." And again, here's diff- a whole
different realm, but similar maybe spirit.

00:07:52.088 --> 00:07:56.028
- Yeah, so I had this problem. I tried
to show PDF on an iPad, which should

00:07:56.068 --> 00:07:56.968
not be hard.

00:07:56.988 --> 00:07:59.128
- This is like 15 years
ago, something like that.

00:07:59.248 --> 00:08:03.178
- Yeah. Like the most, the most
random thing ever. And suddenly, I

00:08:03.208 --> 00:08:07.178
had this problem and I, I
wanted to help a friend. And

00:08:07.208 --> 00:08:11.018
there was, there was... Well, not like
nothing existed, but it was just not good.

00:08:11.018 --> 00:08:14.918
And like... Like I tried
it and it was like very,

00:08:14.918 --> 00:08:17.318
"Nah." Like, "Hmm, I can do this better."

00:08:17.328 --> 00:08:21.128
- By the way, for people who don't know,
this led to the development of PS PDF

00:08:21.148 --> 00:08:24.968
kit that's used on a billion devices.
So, the... It turns out that

00:08:24.988 --> 00:08:28.208
it's pretty useful to
be able to open a PDF.

00:08:28.248 --> 00:08:31.088
- You could also make the joke
that I'm really bad at naming.

00:08:32.048 --> 00:08:32.108
- Yeah.

00:08:32.128 --> 00:08:35.828
- Like, name number five on the
current project. And even

00:08:35.908 --> 00:08:39.748
PS PDF doesn't really
roll from the tongue.

00:08:39.788 --> 00:08:42.948
- Anyway, so you said "Screw it. Why don't

00:08:43.288 --> 00:08:47.128
I do it?" So what was the... What was
the prototype? What was the thing that

00:08:47.228 --> 00:08:51.208
you... What was the magical thing that you built
in a short amount of time that you were like,

00:08:51.228 --> 00:08:55.788
"This might actually work as an agent,"
where I talk to it and it does things?

00:08:55.848 --> 00:08:59.588
- There was... Like, one of my projects
before already did something

00:08:59.608 --> 00:09:03.568
where I could bring my
terminals onto the web and then

00:09:03.628 --> 00:09:06.948
I could, like, interact with them, but
there also would be terminals on my Mac.

00:09:06.968 --> 00:09:07.638
- Mm-hmm.

00:09:07.668 --> 00:09:11.828
- Viptunnel, which was like
a, a weekend hack project

00:09:12.628 --> 00:09:16.348
that was still very early.
And it was cloud code

00:09:16.388 --> 00:09:20.368
times. You know, you got a dopamine hit
when you got something right. And now

00:09:20.388 --> 00:09:22.728
I get, like, mad when
you get something wrong.

00:09:22.768 --> 00:09:26.608
- And you had a really great -– not to take a
tangent -– but a great blog post describing that

00:09:26.728 --> 00:09:30.368
you converted Viptunnel. You vibe-coded

00:09:30.468 --> 00:09:34.378
Viptunnel from TypeScript into Zig
of all programming languages with

00:09:34.488 --> 00:09:40.738
a single prompt. One prompt, one shot.
Convert the entire code base into Zig.

00:09:41.128 --> 00:09:44.388
- Yeah. There was this one thing
where part of the architecture

00:09:46.028 --> 00:09:49.588
was... Took too much
memory. Every terminal

00:09:51.108 --> 00:09:54.648
used like a node. And I
wanted to change it to Rust

00:09:54.708 --> 00:09:59.688
and... I mean, I can do
it. I can, I can manually

00:10:00.648 --> 00:10:06.728
figure it all out, but all my
automated attempts failed miserably.

00:10:08.628 --> 00:10:12.588
And then I revisited about four
or five months later. And I'm

00:10:12.628 --> 00:10:16.228
like, "Okay, now let's use something
even more experimental." And

00:10:16.328 --> 00:10:20.008
I, and I just typed, "Convert
this and this part to

00:10:20.108 --> 00:10:23.638
Sig," and then let Codex run off. And

00:10:23.688 --> 00:10:27.338
it basically got it right. There was
one little detail that I had to,

00:10:27.388 --> 00:10:31.528
like, modify afterwards,
but it just ran for

00:10:32.988 --> 00:10:36.208
overnight or like six hours and
just did its thing. And it's

00:10:36.268 --> 00:10:38.408
like... It's just mind-blowing.

00:10:39.388 --> 00:10:46.298
- So that's on the LLM programming side,
refactoring. But uh, back to the

00:10:46.368 --> 00:10:49.968
actual story of the of the prototype. So
how did Viptunnel connect to the first

00:10:50.028 --> 00:10:52.568
prototype where your, like,
agents can actually work?

00:10:52.648 --> 00:10:56.228
- Well, that was still very limited.
You know, like I had this one

00:10:56.268 --> 00:11:00.288
experiment with WhatsApp, then I had
this experiment, and both felt like

00:11:01.648 --> 00:11:04.148
not the right answer. And then

00:11:06.288 --> 00:11:10.088
my search bar was literally
just hooking up WhatsApp to

00:11:10.148 --> 00:11:17.568
cloud code. One shot. The CLI message comes
in. I call the CLI with -p. It does its

00:11:17.608 --> 00:11:21.528
magic, I get the string back and I send
it back to WhatsApp. And I, I built

00:11:21.548 --> 00:11:23.488
this in one hour. And

00:11:24.688 --> 00:11:28.328
I felt... Already felt really cool. It's
like, "Oh, I could... I can, like, talk to my

00:11:28.368 --> 00:11:32.068
computer," right? This... That,
that was, that was cool. But

00:11:32.168 --> 00:11:35.908
I, I wanted images, 'cause I
alw- I often use images when I

00:11:35.968 --> 00:11:39.728
prompt. I think it's such a, such an
efficient way to give the agent more

00:11:39.768 --> 00:11:43.408
context. And they are really good at figuring
out what I mean, e- even if it's like

00:11:43.508 --> 00:11:47.468
a, a weird cropped-up screenshot. So
I used it a lot and I wanted to do

00:11:47.508 --> 00:11:51.878
that in WhatsApp as well. Also, like, you
know, just you run around, you see like

00:11:52.968 --> 00:11:55.588
a poster of an event, you just
make a screenshot and like

00:11:56.768 --> 00:12:00.118
figure out if I have time there, if this is
good, if my friends are maybe up for that.

00:12:00.118 --> 00:12:04.048
Just like images seemed im-
important. So I, I worked

00:12:04.068 --> 00:12:07.968
a few... It took me a few more hours
to actually get that right. Um,

00:12:09.468 --> 00:12:16.356
and then it was just...... I, I used
it a lot. And funny enough, that was

00:12:17.836 --> 00:12:21.536
just before I went on a trip
to Marrakesh with my friends

00:12:22.016 --> 00:12:25.616
for a birthday trip. And there
it was even better because

00:12:26.296 --> 00:12:30.196
internet was a little shaky but WhatsApp
just works, you know? It's like doesn't

00:12:30.256 --> 00:12:33.316
matter, you have, like, edge,
it still works. WhatsApp is

00:12:33.356 --> 00:12:41.136
just... It's just made really well.
So I ended up using it a lot. Um,

00:12:41.176 --> 00:12:44.996
translate this for me, explain
this, find me places. Like, you

00:12:45.076 --> 00:12:47.996
just having a clanker
doing, having Google for

00:12:48.096 --> 00:12:52.086
you, that was... Basically there
was still nothing built but

00:12:52.096 --> 00:12:53.415
it still could do so much.

00:12:53.836 --> 00:12:57.536
- So, if we talk about the full journey
that's happening there with the agent,

00:12:58.196 --> 00:13:02.496
you're just sending on this
very thin line WhatsApp message

00:13:03.376 --> 00:13:07.376
via CLI, it's going to a cloud code
and cloud code is doing all kinds of

00:13:08.336 --> 00:13:13.156
heavy work and coming back
to you with a thin message.

00:13:13.196 --> 00:13:19.056
- Yeah. It was slow because every time I boot
up the CLI, but it... It was really cool

00:13:19.096 --> 00:13:23.036
already. And it could just use
all the things that I already had

00:13:23.056 --> 00:13:29.296
built. I had built like a whole bunch of
CLI stuff over the month so it, it felt

00:13:30.316 --> 00:13:31.576
really powerful.

00:13:31.616 --> 00:13:34.596
- There is something magical about that
experience that's hard to put into

00:13:34.606 --> 00:13:38.366
words. Being able to use a chat client

00:13:40.236 --> 00:13:44.206
to talk to an agent, versus,
like, sitting behind

00:13:44.236 --> 00:13:47.736
a computer and like, I don't know, using

00:13:47.896 --> 00:13:51.836
cursor or even using Cloud Code CLI in the
terminal. It's a different experience than being

00:13:51.856 --> 00:13:55.736
able to sit back and talk to it. I
mean, it seems like a trivial step

00:13:55.896 --> 00:14:00.336
but, it- in some sense it's
a... It's like a phase shift

00:14:01.236 --> 00:14:05.276
in the integration of AI into your
life and how it feels, right?

00:14:05.316 --> 00:14:09.296
- Yeah. Yeah. I, I read this tweet this
morning where someone said, "Oh, there's

00:14:09.336 --> 00:14:11.016
no magic in it. It's just like,

00:14:12.096 --> 00:14:15.456
it does this and this and this and
this and this and this." And it

00:14:16.756 --> 00:14:20.516
almost feels like a hobby, just
as cursor or perplexity. And I'm

00:14:20.576 --> 00:14:23.856
like, well, if that's a hobby
that's kind of a compliment, you

00:14:23.896 --> 00:14:31.156
know? They're like, they're not
doing too bad. Thank you I guess?

00:14:32.376 --> 00:14:36.106
Yes. I mean, isn't, isn't,
isn't magic often just

00:14:36.196 --> 00:14:38.376
like you take a lot of things
that are already there

00:14:39.236 --> 00:14:43.106
but bring them together in new
ways? Like, I don't... There's

00:14:43.176 --> 00:14:46.676
no... Yeah. Maybe there's no
magic in there but sometimes just

00:14:46.736 --> 00:14:51.316
rearranging things and, like, adding a few
new ideas is all the magic that you need.

00:14:51.396 --> 00:14:55.216
- It's really hard to convert into
words what is, what is magic

00:14:55.276 --> 00:14:58.776
about a thing. If you look
at the, the scrolling on an

00:14:58.856 --> 00:15:02.436
iPhone, why is that so pleasant?
There's a lot of elements about that

00:15:02.496 --> 00:15:06.316
interface that makes it incredibly pleasant,
that is fundamental to the experience of

00:15:06.376 --> 00:15:10.156
using a smartphone, and it's like,
okay, all the components were

00:15:10.196 --> 00:15:13.096
there. Scrolling was there,
everything was there.

00:15:13.256 --> 00:15:14.216
- Nobody did it-

00:15:14.276 --> 00:15:14.415
- Yep

00:15:14.536 --> 00:15:16.165
- ... and afterwards it felt so obvious.

00:15:16.276 --> 00:15:16.856
- Yeah, so obvious.

00:15:16.876 --> 00:15:21.156
- Right? But still... You
know the moment where

