So eventually, I, I, I went back

01:02:16.296 --> 01:02:22.238
to cloud code as my, my main
driver, and that got better.

01:02:23.158 --> 01:02:29.038
And yeah, at some point I had
like, mm, seven subscriptions.

01:02:31.377 --> 01:02:35.278
Like, was burning through one per day
because I was... I got... I'm really

01:02:35.317 --> 01:02:40.218
comfortable at running
multiple windows side-by-side.

01:02:40.298 --> 01:02:46.517
- All CLI, all terminal. So like, what, how
much were you using IDE at this point?

01:02:46.678 --> 01:02:53.538
- Um, very, very rarely. Mostly a
diff viewer to actually... Like,

01:02:54.377 --> 01:02:58.138
I got more and more comfortable that I don't
have to read all the code. I know I have

01:02:58.337 --> 01:03:01.437
one blog post where I say, "I don't read the
code." But if you read it more closely, I

01:03:01.497 --> 01:03:04.997
mean, I don't read the boring
parts of code. Because if

01:03:05.058 --> 01:03:08.517
you, if you look at it, most
software is really not just like

01:03:09.397 --> 01:03:13.118
data comes in, it's moved
from one shape to another

01:03:13.138 --> 01:03:17.017
shape. Maybe you store it in a database.
Maybe I get it out again. I'll show it to

01:03:17.058 --> 01:03:20.298
the user. The browser does
some processing or native

01:03:20.417 --> 01:03:24.187
app. Some data goes in, goes up
again, and does the same dance in

01:03:24.218 --> 01:03:32.028
reverse. We're just, we're just shifting
data from one form to another, and

01:03:32.058 --> 01:03:33.087
that's not very exciting.

01:03:33.997 --> 01:03:37.937
Or the whole, "How is my button aligned
in Tailwind?" I don't need to read that

01:03:38.018 --> 01:03:45.877
code. Other parts that... Maybe
something that touches the database. Um,

01:03:46.357 --> 01:03:49.638
yeah, I have to do... I have to
r- read and review that code.

01:03:51.678 --> 01:03:55.348
- Can you actually... There's, in
one of your blog posts the, Just

01:03:55.457 --> 01:03:58.908
talk to it, The No-BS Way of
Agentic Engineering. You have this

01:03:58.957 --> 01:04:02.857
graphic, the curve of agentic programming
on the X-axis is time, on the

01:04:02.977 --> 01:04:09.698
Y-axis is complexity. There's the Please
fix this, where you prompt a short

01:04:09.778 --> 01:04:13.738
prompt on the left. And in the

01:04:13.798 --> 01:04:17.118
middle there's super complicated
eight agents, complex

01:04:17.158 --> 01:04:20.837
orchestration with multi checkouts,
chaining agents together,

01:04:20.897 --> 01:04:24.537
custom sub-agent workflows, library
of 18 different slash commands, large

01:04:24.618 --> 01:04:28.337
full-stack features. You're super
organized, you're a super complicated,

01:04:28.397 --> 01:04:32.317
sophisticated software engineer.
You got everything organized. And

01:04:32.357 --> 01:04:39.558
then the elite level is over time you arrive
at the zen place of, once again, short

01:04:39.678 --> 01:04:45.417
prompts. Hey, look at these
files and then do these changes.

01:04:45.477 --> 01:04:51.868
- I actually call it the agentic
trap. You... I saw this in a, in

01:04:52.977 --> 01:04:55.298
a lot of people that have
their first touchpoint,

01:04:56.558 --> 01:05:01.018
and maybe start vibe coding. I
actually think vibe coding is a slur.

01:05:01.098 --> 01:05:02.857
- You prefer agentic engineering?

01:05:02.877 --> 01:05:06.758
- Yeah, I always tell people I, I do
agentic engineering, and then maybe after

01:05:06.957 --> 01:05:10.578
3:00 AM I switch to vibe coding, and
then I have regrets on the next day.

01:05:10.638 --> 01:05:13.698
- Yeah. Walk, walk of shame.

01:05:13.718 --> 01:05:16.997
- Yeah, you just have to clean
up and like fix your sh- shit.

01:05:17.058 --> 01:05:18.178
- We've all been there.

01:05:18.258 --> 01:05:22.058
- So, people start trying out
those tools, the builder

01:05:22.118 --> 01:05:24.988
type get really excited. And then

01:05:26.298 --> 01:05:30.176
you have to play with it, right? It's
the same way as you have to play with a

01:05:30.218 --> 01:05:33.357
guitar before you can make
good music. It's, it's

01:05:33.397 --> 01:05:37.118
not, oh, I, I touch it
once and it just flows

01:05:37.218 --> 01:05:41.127
off. It, it's a, it's a,
a skill that you have

01:05:41.127 --> 01:05:48.678
to learn like any other skill. And I
see a lot of people that are not as

01:05:48.758 --> 01:05:52.837
posi- They don't have such a positive
mindset towards the tech. They try it once.

01:05:53.977 --> 01:05:57.937
It's like, you sit me on a
piano, I play it once, and it

01:05:57.977 --> 01:06:01.857
doesn't sound good, and I say, "The piano's shit."
That's, that's sometimes the impression I get.

01:06:01.877 --> 01:06:07.028
Because it does not... It needs a
different level of thinking. You have to

01:06:09.558 --> 01:06:13.118
learn the language of the agent a
little bit, understand where they are

01:06:13.198 --> 01:06:20.558
good and where they need help. You
have to almost... Consider, consider

01:06:20.638 --> 01:06:25.698
how Codex or Claude sees your code
base. Like, they start a new session

01:06:25.738 --> 01:06:29.678
and they know nothing about your product, project.
And your project might have hundred thousand

01:06:29.718 --> 01:06:33.817
of lines of code. So you gotta
help those agents a little bit

01:06:34.618 --> 01:06:36.278
and keep in mind the limitations that

01:06:37.078 --> 01:06:41.607
context size is an issue, to, like,
guide them a little bit as to

01:06:42.638 --> 01:06:50.368
where they should look. That often does
not require a whole lot of work. But

01:06:50.417 --> 01:06:54.457
it's helpful to think a little
bit about their perspective.

01:06:54.477 --> 01:06:54.877
- Mm-hmm.

01:06:54.937 --> 01:06:58.037
- A- as, as weird as it sounds. I mean, it's
not, it's not alive or anything, right?

01:06:58.058 --> 01:07:05.477
But, but they always start fresh. I have,
I have the, the system understanding.

01:07:05.578 --> 01:07:09.558
So with a few pointers, I can immediately
say, "Hey, wanna like, make a

01:07:09.618 --> 01:07:13.558
change there? You need to consider this, this and
this." And then they will find and look at it, and then

01:07:13.598 --> 01:07:17.457
they'll... Their view of the project
is always... It's not never full,

01:07:17.497 --> 01:07:21.328
because the full thing does not fit
in.... so you, you have to guide them a

01:07:21.378 --> 01:07:25.148
little bit where to look
and also how you should

01:07:25.178 --> 01:07:28.388
approach the problem. There's, like,
little things that sometimes help,

01:07:28.438 --> 01:07:35.678
like take your time. That sounds
stupid, but... And in 5.3-

01:07:35.738 --> 01:07:36.698
- Codex 5.3

01:07:36.708 --> 01:07:40.537
- ... that was partially
addressed. But those...

01:07:41.238 --> 01:07:44.758
Also, Opus sometimes. They are trained,

01:07:44.838 --> 01:07:48.718
With being aware of the context
window, and the closer it

01:07:48.758 --> 01:07:52.598
gets, the more they freak out. Literally.

01:07:52.618 --> 01:07:56.098
Like, some- sometimes you see
the, the real raw thinking

01:07:56.158 --> 01:07:59.378
stream. What you see, for example,
in Codex, is post-processed.

01:07:59.398 --> 01:08:00.218
- Mm-hmm.

01:08:00.278 --> 01:08:03.618
- Sometimes the actual raw thinking stream leaks
in, and it sounds something like from the

01:08:03.658 --> 01:08:08.798
Borg. Like, "Run to
shell, must comply, but

01:08:08.838 --> 01:08:12.718
time." And then they, they,

01:08:12.738 --> 01:08:15.918
they, like... Like, that comes
up a lot. Especially... So, so-

01:08:15.938 --> 01:08:16.858
- Yeah.

01:08:16.868 --> 01:08:20.578
- And that's, that's a
non-obvious thing that you just

01:08:21.018 --> 01:08:24.998
would never think of unless
you actually just spend time

01:08:26.038 --> 01:08:28.178
working with those things
and getting a feeling

01:08:29.118 --> 01:08:32.938
what works, what doesn't work. You
know? Like, just, just as I write

01:08:33.038 --> 01:08:38.058
code and I get into the flow, and when my
architecture's all right, I feel friction.

01:08:39.417 --> 01:08:43.238
Well, I get the same if I prompt
and something takes too long.

01:08:43.318 --> 01:08:46.638
Maybe... Okay, where's the mistake?
Did I... Do I have a mistake in my

01:08:46.658 --> 01:08:49.258
thinking? Is there, like,
a misunderstanding in the

01:08:49.298 --> 01:08:53.138
architecture? Like, if, if something takes

01:08:53.238 --> 01:08:57.078
longer than it should, I, I... You can just
always, like, stop and s- like, just press

01:08:57.118 --> 01:08:59.978
escape. Where, where are the problems?

01:09:00.018 --> 01:09:03.948
- Maybe you did not sufficiently empathize with
the perspective of the agent. In that c- in

01:09:03.998 --> 01:09:07.977
that sense, you didn't provide enough information,
and because of that, it's thinking way

01:09:08.018 --> 01:09:08.618
too long.

01:09:08.678 --> 01:09:12.417
- Yeah. It just tries to
force a feature in that

01:09:13.158 --> 01:09:17.298
your current architecture
makes really hard. Um,

01:09:18.778 --> 01:09:24.018
like, you need to approach this more
like a conversation. For example, when

01:09:24.118 --> 01:09:27.118
I... My favorite thing.
When I review a pull

01:09:27.158 --> 01:09:30.578
request, and I'm getting
a lot of pull requests,

01:09:32.358 --> 01:09:36.218
I first just review this PR.
It got me the review. My

01:09:36.258 --> 01:09:39.978
first question is, "Do you understand
the intent of the PR? I don't

01:09:40.078 --> 01:09:43.908
even care about the
implementation." I want...

01:09:43.958 --> 01:09:47.678
Like, in almost all PRs,
a person has a problem,

01:09:48.078 --> 01:09:51.917
person tries to solve the problem, person
sends PR. I mean, there's, like, cleanup

01:09:51.958 --> 01:09:55.778
stuff and other stuff, but, like, 99% is,
like, this way, right? They either want to fix

01:09:55.838 --> 01:10:00.838
a, fix a bug, add a feature.
Usually one of those two.

01:10:01.678 --> 01:10:03.278
And then Codex will be like, "Yeah,

01:10:04.378 --> 01:10:08.158
it's quite clear person tried this and
this." Is this the most optimal way to do

01:10:08.198 --> 01:10:12.058
it? No. In most cases, it's, it's like a,

01:10:12.068 --> 01:10:15.738
"Not really." Da-da-da-da-da-da-da.
And I'm... And, and then I start like,

01:10:15.748 --> 01:10:19.478
"Okay. What would be a better way?
Have you... Have you looked into this

01:10:19.518 --> 01:10:23.427
part, this part, this part?" And then most
likely, Codex didn't yet, because its,

01:10:23.438 --> 01:10:27.148
its context size is empty, right? So, you
point them into parts where you have the

01:10:27.198 --> 01:10:30.948
system understanding that it didn't
see yet. And it's like, "Oh,

01:10:30.978 --> 01:10:34.958
yeah. Like, we should... We also need to consider this
and this." And then, like, we have a discussion of how

01:10:34.978 --> 01:10:38.798
would the optimal way to, to solve this
look like? And then you can still go

01:10:38.918 --> 01:10:42.718
farther and say, "Could we... Could
we make that even better if we did a

01:10:42.738 --> 01:10:46.578
larger refactor?" "Yeah, yeah. We could totally do
this and this and or this and this." And then I

01:10:46.618 --> 01:10:50.118
consider, okay, is this worth the refactor,
or should we, like, keep that for

01:10:50.158 --> 01:10:53.798
later? Many times, I just
do the refactor because

01:10:53.838 --> 01:10:56.668
refactors are cheap now. Even though
you might break some other PRs,

01:10:57.718 --> 01:11:00.958
nothing really matters anymore. Codex...
Like, those modern agents will just

01:11:01.538 --> 01:11:03.478
figure things out. They might
just take a minute longer.

01:11:04.318 --> 01:11:09.308
But you have to approach it like a
discussion with a, a very capable

01:11:10.178 --> 01:11:15.158
engineer who's... Generally makes

01:11:15.198 --> 01:11:19.958
good... Comes up with good solutions.
Some- sometimes needs a little help.

01:11:19.978 --> 01:11:23.958
- But also, don't force your
worldview too hard on

01:11:23.998 --> 01:11:27.778
it. Let the agent do the
thing that it's good at

01:11:27.818 --> 01:11:31.798
doing, based on what it was trained
on. So, don't, like, force your

01:11:31.838 --> 01:11:35.698
worldview, because it might... It might
have a better idea, because it just knows

01:11:35.758 --> 01:11:39.498
a better idea better, because
it was trained on that more.

01:11:39.598 --> 01:11:42.378
- That's multiple levels,
actually. I think partially why

01:11:42.388 --> 01:11:46.178
I find it quite easy
to work with agents is

01:11:46.258 --> 01:11:49.298
because I led engineering teams before.
You know, I had a large company

01:11:49.338 --> 01:11:53.198
before. And eventually, you have to
understand and accept and realize

01:11:53.238 --> 01:11:56.978
that your employees will not
write a code the same way you do.

01:11:57.048 --> 01:12:00.758
Maybe it's also not as good
as you would do, but it will

01:12:00.858 --> 01:12:04.778
push the project forward. And if I
breathe down everyone's neck, they're

01:12:04.818 --> 01:12:05.678
just gonna hate me-

01:12:05.698 --> 01:12:05.708
- Yeah

01:12:05.708 --> 01:12:07.038
- ... and we're gonna move very slow.

01:12:07.098 --> 01:12:07.498
- Yeah.

01:12:07.558 --> 01:12:11.358
- So, so some level of acceptance that, yes,

01:12:11.418 --> 01:12:15.078
maybe the code will not be as perfect.
Yes, I would have done it differently.

01:12:15.958 --> 01:12:19.838
But also, yes, this is a c-
this is a working solution, and

01:12:19.998 --> 01:12:23.678
in the future, if it actually turns out to
be too slow or problematic, we can always

01:12:23.758 --> 01:12:28.398
redo it. We can always- ... spend more
time on it. A lot of the people who

01:12:28.478 --> 01:12:33.018
struggle are those who, they try
to push their way onto heart.

01:12:33.038 --> 01:12:33.698
- Mm-hmm.

01:12:33.758 --> 01:12:40.418
- I- i- like, we are in a stage where
I'm not building the code base to be

01:12:41.558 --> 01:12:45.518
perfect for me, but I wanna
build a code base that

01:12:45.538 --> 01:12:47.778
is very easy for an agent to navigate.

01:12:47.798 --> 01:12:48.678
- Mm-hmm.

01:12:48.688 --> 01:12:52.518
- So, like, don't fight the name they
pick, because it's most likely,

01:12:52.558 --> 01:12:56.338
like, in the weights, the name that's most obvious.
Next time they do a search, they'll look for that

01:12:56.398 --> 01:12:58.558
name. If I decide, oh,
no, I don't like the

01:12:58.598 --> 01:13:02.528
name, I'll just make it
harder for them. So,

01:13:02.578 --> 01:13:08.218
that requires, I think, a shift
in, in thinking, And, and in

01:13:09.078 --> 01:13:14.918
how do I design a, a project so
agents can do their best work.

01:13:14.978 --> 01:13:18.998
- That requires letting go a little bit.
Just like leading a team of engineers.

01:13:19.038 --> 01:13:19.378
- Yeah.

01:13:19.398 --> 01:13:22.338
- Because it, it might come up with
a name that's, in your view,

01:13:22.398 --> 01:13:29.554
terrible, but... It's kind of a simple
symbolic-... step of letting go.

01:13:29.674 --> 01:13:30.694
- Very much so.

01:13:30.714 --> 01:13:34.574
- There's a lot of letting go that you
do in your whole process. So for

01:13:34.614 --> 01:13:37.394
example, I read that you never revert,

01:13:39.054 --> 01:13:41.974
always commit to main.
There's a few things here.

01:13:43.854 --> 01:13:47.794
You don't refer to past sessions,
so there's a kind of YOLO component

01:13:47.854 --> 01:13:53.374
because reverting means...
Instead of reverting, if a

01:13:53.414 --> 01:13:56.934
problem comes up, you just
ask the agent to fix it.

01:13:57.034 --> 01:14:00.994
- I read a bunch of people in their work flows
like, "Oh, yeah the prompt has to be perfect

01:14:01.034 --> 01:14:04.754
and if I make a mistake, then
I roll back and redo it all."

01:14:05.494 --> 01:14:09.434
In my experience, that's not really necessary.
If I roll back everything, it will just

01:14:09.494 --> 01:14:15.334
take longer. If I see that something's not
good, then we just move forward and then

01:14:16.754 --> 01:14:21.554
I commit when, when, when I like, I
like the outcome. I even switched to

01:14:24.374 --> 01:14:30.214
local CI, you know, like DHH inspired
where I don't care so much more about

01:14:31.154 --> 01:14:39.014
the CI on GitHub. We still have it. It's
still, it still has a place, but I just

01:14:39.074 --> 01:14:42.964
run tests locally and if they
work locally, I push to main.

01:14:44.314 --> 01:14:52.234
A lot of the traditional ways how to
approach projects, I, I wanted to give it

01:14:52.374 --> 01:14:56.014
a different spin on this project.
You know, there's no... There's no

01:14:56.034 --> 01:14:59.874
develop branch. Main should
always be shippable.

01:14:59.954 --> 01:15:07.274
Yes, we have... When I do releases, I, I
run tests and sometimes I, I basically

01:15:07.514 --> 01:15:14.514
don't commit any other things so, so we
can, we can stabilize releases. But the

01:15:14.554 --> 01:15:18.854
goal is that main's always
shippable and moving fast.

01:15:18.914 --> 01:15:23.334
- So by way of advice, would you say
that your prompts should be short?

01:15:23.414 --> 01:15:27.374
- I used to write really long
prompts. And by writing, I

01:15:27.414 --> 01:15:31.094
mean, I don't write. I, I, I talk.
You know, th- these hands are, like,

01:15:31.134 --> 01:15:34.814
too, too precious for writing
now. I just, I just use

01:15:34.894 --> 01:15:37.014
bespoke prompts to build my software.

01:15:37.054 --> 01:15:40.854
- So you for real with all those
terminals are using voice?

01:15:40.894 --> 01:15:43.694
- Yeah. I used to do it very extensively

01:15:44.994 --> 01:15:47.834
to the point where there was a
period where I lost my voice.

01:15:49.034 --> 01:15:52.174
- You're using voice and you're switching
using a keyboard between the different

01:15:52.183 --> 01:15:55.334
terminals, but then you're using
voice for the actual input.

01:15:55.394 --> 01:15:57.204
- Well, I mean, if I do
terminal commands like

01:15:58.834 --> 01:16:02.734
switching folders or random stuff, of course
I type. It's faster, right? But if I talk

01:16:02.774 --> 01:16:06.284
to the agent in, in most
ways, I just actually have a

01:16:06.294 --> 01:16:11.554
conversation. You just press the, the
walkie-talkie button and then I just, like,

01:16:13.194 --> 01:16:17.154
use my phrases. S- sometimes when I do
PRs because it's always the same, I

01:16:17.194 --> 01:16:23.054
have, like, a slash command for a few
things, but in even that, I don't use much,

01:16:23.174 --> 01:16:28.574
um, because it's, it's very rare that
it's really always the same questions.

01:16:28.634 --> 01:16:36.224
Sometimes I, I see a PR and for... You
know, like for PRs I actually do look

01:16:36.254 --> 01:16:40.204
at the code because I don't trust people.

01:16:41.114 --> 01:16:45.054
Like, there could always be something malicious
in it, so I need to actually look over the code.

01:16:45.074 --> 01:16:50.014
Yes, I'm pretty sure agents will find it,
but yeah, that's the funny part where

01:16:51.014 --> 01:16:54.614
sometimes PRs take me longer than if
you would just write me a good issue.

01:16:54.734 --> 01:16:58.344
- Just natural language, English.
I mean in some sense, sh-

01:16:58.654 --> 01:17:03.834
shouldn't that be what PRs
slowly become, is English?

01:17:03.874 --> 01:17:08.574
- Well, what I really tried with the project
is I asked people to give me the prompts

01:17:09.654 --> 01:17:15.534
and very, very few actually cared.
Even though that is such a wonderful

01:17:15.574 --> 01:17:18.974
indicator because I see... I
actually see how much care you put

01:17:19.054 --> 01:17:24.774
in. And it's very interesting because
the... Currently, the way how people work

01:17:25.774 --> 01:17:29.194
and drive the agents is,
is wildly different.

01:17:29.894 --> 01:17:33.654
- In terms of, like, the prompt, in terms of what,
what are the... Actually, what are the different

01:17:34.834 --> 01:17:40.254
interesting ways that people think
of agents that you've experienced?

01:17:40.354 --> 01:17:44.213
- I think not a lot of people
ever considered the way

01:17:45.054 --> 01:17:46.794
the agent sees the world.

01:17:46.814 --> 01:17:49.754
- And so empathy, being
empathetic towards the agent.

01:17:50.294 --> 01:17:53.494
- In a way empathetic, but yeah, you,
you, like, you're bitch at your stupid

01:17:53.534 --> 01:17:57.434
clanker, but you don't realize that
they start from nothing and you have,

01:17:57.454 --> 01:18:01.294
like, a bad agent in default that doesn't
help them at all. And then they explore your

01:18:01.314 --> 01:18:05.194
code base, which is, like, a pure
mess with, like, weird naming.

