01:35:02.838 --> 01:35:06.598
slow. Like, often it would give me
four questions and then maybe I write,

01:35:07.358 --> 01:35:14.738
"One yacht, two and three, discuss more,
four, I don't know." Or often- oftentimes

01:35:14.818 --> 01:35:18.518
I- I feel like I want to mock the model where
I ask it, "Do you have any questions for

01:35:18.598 --> 01:35:22.577
me?" And I- I- I don't even read
the questions fully. Like, I scan

01:35:22.598 --> 01:35:26.208
over the questions and I, I get
the impression all of this can

01:35:26.258 --> 01:35:29.798
be answered by reading more code and it's
just like, "Read more code to answer your own

01:35:29.818 --> 01:35:32.018
questions." And that usually works.

01:35:32.098 --> 01:35:32.268
- Yeah.

01:35:32.378 --> 01:35:34.577
- And then if not, it will
come back and tell me. But

01:35:35.758 --> 01:35:37.358
many times, you just realize that,

01:35:38.338 --> 01:35:41.778
you know, it's like you're in the
dark and you slowly discover the

01:35:41.838 --> 01:35:45.478
room, so that's how they slowly discover
the code base. And they do it from

01:35:45.558 --> 01:35:46.718
scratch every time.

01:35:46.758 --> 01:35:51.758
- But I'm also fascinated by the
fact that I can empathize deeper

01:35:53.058 --> 01:35:58.217
with the model when I read
its questions, because I can

01:35:58.258 --> 01:36:04.018
understand... Because you said you can
infer certain things by the runtime.

01:36:05.077 --> 01:36:08.178
I can infer also a lot of
things by the questions it's

01:36:08.278 --> 01:36:11.738
asking, because it's very possible
it's been provided the right

01:36:12.178 --> 01:36:15.878
context, the right files, the
right guidance. So somehow

01:36:15.998 --> 01:36:19.978
ask, g- get... reading the questions, not even
necessarily answering them, but just reading

01:36:20.018 --> 01:36:23.998
the questions, you get an understanding of
where the gaps of knowledge are. It's in-

01:36:24.038 --> 01:36:24.618
it's interesting.

01:36:24.758 --> 01:36:28.598
- You know that in some ways they are
ghosts, so even if you plan everything

01:36:29.258 --> 01:36:33.238
and you build, you can- you can
experiment with the question like,

01:36:33.318 --> 01:36:36.998
"Now that you built it, what
would you have done different?"

01:36:37.318 --> 01:36:40.458
And then oftentimes you get,
like, actually something where

01:36:41.538 --> 01:36:45.338
they discover only throughout
building that, oh, what we

01:36:45.378 --> 01:36:48.998
actually did was not optimal.
Many times I- I asked

01:36:49.018 --> 01:36:52.778
them, "Okay, now that you
built it, what can we

01:36:52.818 --> 01:36:56.758
refactor?" Because then you
build it and you feel the

01:36:56.798 --> 01:37:00.758
pain points. I mean, you don't
feel the pain points but, right,

01:37:00.798 --> 01:37:04.258
they discover where- where there
were problems or where things

01:37:05.338 --> 01:37:10.258
didn't work e- in the first try
and it re- required more loops. So

01:37:11.958 --> 01:37:15.378
every time, almost every time
I- I merge a PR, build a

01:37:15.418 --> 01:37:19.138
feature, afterwards I ask, "Hey, what
can we refactor?" Sometimes it's

01:37:19.178 --> 01:37:22.327
like, "No, there's, like, nothing
big," or, like, usually they say,

01:37:22.327 --> 01:37:28.678
"Yeah, this thing you should
really look at." But that took me

01:37:28.738 --> 01:37:32.438
quite a while to, like... You know,
that flow took me lots of time to

01:37:32.478 --> 01:37:36.198
understand, and if you don't do
that, you eventually... you'll stop

01:37:36.238 --> 01:37:40.458
yourself into- into a corner. You,
like, you have to keep in mind...

01:37:41.838 --> 01:37:42.028
- ...

01:37:42.038 --> 01:37:45.928
- ... they work very much like humans.
Like, I, I, if I write software

01:37:45.978 --> 01:37:49.138
by myself, I also build something and
then I feel the pain points, and then

01:37:49.318 --> 01:37:53.278
I, I get this urge that I
need to refactor something.

01:37:53.338 --> 01:38:00.117
So, I can very much synthesize with the
agent, and you just need to use the context.

01:38:00.138 --> 01:38:00.438
- Mm-hmm.

01:38:00.498 --> 01:38:05.138
- Or, like, you also use the
context to write tests. And so,

01:38:06.117 --> 01:38:09.168
uh, Codex uh, oppose like
